{"rows":[{"experiment":"1a","prompting_strategy":"zero-shot classification","source_output_list":"base_output","evaluation_list":"experiment_1a_accuracy","model":"gpt-4.1-mini","dataset":"ag_news_small","n_articles":10,"accuracy":0.9},{"experiment":"1b","prompting_strategy":"reasoning-augmented classification","source_output_list":"reason_output","evaluation_list":"experiment_1b_accuracy","model":"gpt-4.1-mini","dataset":"ag_news_small","n_articles":10,"accuracy":0.9},{"experiment":"1c","prompting_strategy":"few-shot classification","source_output_list":"few_shot_output","evaluation_list":"experiment_1c_accuracy","model":"gpt-4.1-mini","dataset":"ag_news_small","n_articles":10,"accuracy":0.9}],"summary":"The repository contains a direct comparison of three prompting strategies for LLM-based document classification on a small AG News sample: zero-shot classification (experiment 1a), reasoning-augmented classification (experiment 1b), and few-shot classification using four handwritten examples (experiment 1c). All three were evaluated with the same model, gpt-4.1-mini, on the same 10 sampled articles, and each achieved identical exact-match accuracy of 0.90. At the evidence level available here, few-shot examples did not improve accuracy relative to the zero-shot baseline.

Inspection of the row-level outputs supports this interpretation: the zero-shot, reasoning-augmented, and few-shot runs appear to make the same single error, predicting Business for one World-labeled article about Chinese inflation. This suggests that the classification difficulty in this sample arises from topic overlap between geopolitical and economic news, and that adding few-shot demonstrations was not sufficient to resolve that ambiguity.

However, the evidence is limited. The evaluation set is very small (n=10), so the study is underpowered and a 0.90 accuracy estimate has high uncertainty. Because only one few-shot configuration is represented, the repository does not show whether different examples, prompt wording, larger context windows, or a broader test set might produce gains. Therefore, the strongest supported conclusion is narrow: in this repository's available AG News experiment, few-shot prompting did not outperform zero-shot prompting for document classification accuracy."}
